Note:
==============================================================================
KEYPAIR - Algorithm-agnostic keypair container with PKCS#8 / SPKI encoding
==============================================================================

This module extends the lower-level key_pair.runa primitive (which carries the
PrivateKey/PublicKey pair) by:

  1. Providing algorithm-agnostic random keypair generation across the FULL
     algorithm set defined by crypto_algorithm.runa: Ed25519/Ed448, ECDSA
     over NIST curves, RSA-{2048,3072,4096}, X25519/X448, ML-KEM-{512,768,
     1024}, ML-DSA-{44,65,87}, SLH-DSA-SHA2-{128s,128f,192s,192f,256s,256f},
     and FALCON-{512,1024}. The ML-KEM, ML-DSA, and SLH-DSA keygen paths
     all run on integer-only arithmetic per FIPS 203/204/205, so they are
     supported on every host. FALCON keygen requires Float64 SSE2 for the
     NTRU-lattice sampler (the FFT operates on IEEE 754 doubles) and the
     capability check refuses keygen for FALCON-512 and FALCON-1024 until
     the in-tree Float64 SSE2 path is wired in.

  2. Encoding keypairs into PKCS#8 PrivateKeyInfo (RFC 5958) DER and decoding
     them back; encoding public keys into SubjectPublicKeyInfo (RFC 5280)
     DER and decoding them back. The DER encoder is hand-rolled (no
     asn1_der.runa dependency for the encode path, because asn1_der.runa is
     a parser-only library; encoding is short and explicit here).

  3. Secure destruction of the private half via secure_memory.runa.

PKCS#8 PrivateKeyInfo (RFC 5958):
    PrivateKeyInfo ::= SEQUENCE {
        version                   Version,                  -- INTEGER 0
        privateKeyAlgorithm       AlgorithmIdentifier,
        privateKey                OCTET STRING,             -- algorithm-specific
        attributes            [0] IMPLICIT Attributes OPTIONAL -- omitted
    }
    AlgorithmIdentifier ::= SEQUENCE {
        algorithm   OBJECT IDENTIFIER,
        parameters  ANY DEFINED BY algorithm OPTIONAL
    }
    Inner OCTET STRING wrapping (RFC 8410 for Ed25519/Ed448/X25519/X448):
        CurvePrivateKey ::= OCTET STRING

SubjectPublicKeyInfo (RFC 5280):
    SubjectPublicKeyInfo ::= SEQUENCE {
        algorithm        AlgorithmIdentifier,
        subjectPublicKey BIT STRING
    }

References:
- RFC 5958: Asymmetric Key Packages (PKCS#8).
- RFC 5280: Internet X.509 PKI Certificate and CRL Profile (SPKI).
- RFC 8410: Algorithm Identifiers for Ed25519, Ed448, X25519, X448.
- RFC 5208: original PKCS#8 (superseded by RFC 5958 but compatible for v1).
- RFC 5915: ECPrivateKey wrapping for ECDSA.
- RFC 3447 + RFC 8017: RSAPrivateKey / RSAPublicKey wrapping.
- HC#11 TASC: crypto-agility mandate (algorithm tag is authoritative, not
  byte-length).
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/crypto_identity/crypto_algorithm.runa" as Alg
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/crypto_identity/public_key.runa" as PK
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/crypto_identity/private_key.runa" as SK
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/crypto_identity/key_pair.runa" as KP
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/secure_memory.runa" as Secure
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/entropy.runa" as Entropy
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/ed25519.runa" as Ed25519
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/ed448.runa" as Ed448
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/x25519.runa" as X25519
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/x448.runa" as X448
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/ecdsa.runa" as Ecdsa
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/rsa.runa" as Rsa
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/bigint.runa" as BigInt
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/ml_kem.runa" as MlKem
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/ml_dsa.runa" as MlDsa
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/slh_dsa.runa" as SlhDsa

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1: Error codes for keypair_keygen_capability_check
Note: ============================================================================

Let KEYPAIR_CAP_OK be 1
Let KEYPAIR_CAP_FLOAT64_REQUIRED be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2: Algorithm capability probe
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
FALCON keygen requires Float64 SSE2 because the NTRU-lattice basis
generator runs an FFT over IEEE 754 doubles (Fast Fourier sampling per
Falcon spec section 3.8). Until the in-tree Float64 SSE2 path is wired
in, keygen requests for FALCON-512 and FALCON-1024 return a hard error
rather than silently stubbing or producing an invalid key.

ML-KEM (FIPS 203), ML-DSA (FIPS 204), and SLH-DSA (FIPS 205) all run on
integer-only arithmetic: ML-KEM and ML-DSA use a Montgomery-form NTT
over Z_q with q in {3329, 8380417}, and SLH-DSA is hash-based. They are
supported on every host.

The classical algorithms (Ed25519/Ed448, X25519/X448, ECDSA over the NIST
curves, RSA-{2048,3072,4096}) are integer-only and supported on every
host. This proc is the single authoritative capability check that gates
the keypair_create dispatcher.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns KEYPAIR_CAP_OK (1) for every algorithm whose keygen path runs on
integer arithmetic alone. Returns KEYPAIR_CAP_FLOAT64_REQUIRED (0) for
FALCON-512 and FALCON-1024, whose keygen depends on the Float64 SSE2 FFT.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). Single range tests.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Refusing keygen for unsupported algorithms is safer than emitting a stub.
The capability check is data-independent.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_keygen_capability_check" takes algorithm as Integer returns Integer:
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ED25519:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ED448:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_X25519:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_X448:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If Alg.rsa_alg_modulus_bytes(algorithm) is not equal to 0:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    Note: ML-KEM keygen runs integer-only NTT (FIPS 203 Algorithm 13).
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_512:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_768:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_1024:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    Note: ML-DSA keygen runs integer-only NTT (FIPS 204 Algorithm 1).
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_44:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_65:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_87:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    Note: SLH-DSA keygen is hash-based (FIPS 205 Algorithm 18); no FP at all.
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F:
        Return KEYPAIR_CAP_OK
    End If
    Note: FALCON keygen runs the NTRU-lattice FFT over Float64; refuse until
    Note: the Float64 SSE2 path is wired into the in-tree backend.
    Return KEYPAIR_CAP_FLOAT64_REQUIRED
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3: keypair_create - random keygen dispatcher
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Algorithm-agnostic keypair generation. Dispatches on the algorithm tag to
the appropriate algorithm's keygen routine. For Ed25519/Ed448/X25519/X448
this delegates to key_pair.runa's keypair_generate (which handles random
seed draw plus algorithm-specific keygen). For ECDSA, RSA, ML-KEM, ML-DSA,
and SLH-DSA, this module owns the dispatch directly: it allocates the
algorithm-specific PK/SK buffers, draws entropy via entropy.runa, calls
the underlying algorithm keygen, and wraps the resulting byte buffers as
PrivateKey + PublicKey holders.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Validate arena and algorithm.
  2. Check capability via keypair_keygen_capability_check; return 0 if not
     supported on this host.
  3. Dispatch to algorithm-specific keygen:
     - Ed25519/Ed448/X25519/X448: KP.keypair_generate (existing path).
     - ECDSA P256/P384/P521: ecdsa_pNNN_keygen + wrap as PrivateKey/PublicKey.
     - RSA-2048/3072/4096 PSS or PKCS1v15: rsa_keygen + wrap.
     - ML-KEM-512/768/1024: keypair_create_ml_kem helper draws two 32-byte
       seeds (d, z) and calls ml_kem_NNN_keygen.
     - ML-DSA-44/65/87: keypair_create_ml_dsa helper draws a 32-byte
       seed xi and calls ml_dsa_NN_keygen.
     - SLH-DSA-SHA2-{128,192,256}{s,f}: keypair_create_slh_dsa helper
       draws three n-byte seeds (sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed) per FIPS 205
       Algorithm 18 and calls the parameter-set keygen.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(keygen) for the algorithm. RSA-2048 keygen is the slowest at this tier
(seconds on the Miller-Rabin path); the other algorithms complete in
microseconds-to-milliseconds.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Uses OS entropy via entropy_random_bytes inside the algorithm-specific
keygen. Caller arena should be short-lived for keygen to ensure scratch
buffers are reclaimed promptly.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_create" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cap be keypair_keygen_capability_check(algorithm)
    If cap is equal to KEYPAIR_CAP_FLOAT64_REQUIRED:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: For the curve-25519/448 family delegate to the existing keypair_generate path.
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ED25519:
        Return KP.keypair_generate(arena, algorithm)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ED448:
        Return KP.keypair_generate(arena, algorithm)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_X25519:
        Return KP.keypair_generate(arena, algorithm)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_X448:
        Return KP.keypair_generate(arena, algorithm)
    End If

    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Return keypair_create_ecdsa(arena, algorithm, 32)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Return keypair_create_ecdsa(arena, algorithm, 48)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Note: P-521 private scalar fits in 66 bytes, public uncompressed = 1 + 2*66 = 133.
        Return keypair_create_ecdsa(arena, algorithm, 66)
    End If

    Let rsa_modulus_bytes be Alg.rsa_alg_modulus_bytes(algorithm)
    If rsa_modulus_bytes is not equal to 0:
        Let rsa_bits be rsa_modulus_bytes multiplied by 8
        Return keypair_create_rsa(arena, algorithm, rsa_bits)
    End If

    Note: ML-KEM (FIPS 203): ek size = 384*k + 32, dk size = 768*k + 96.
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_512:
        Return keypair_create_ml_kem(arena, algorithm, 1, 800, 1632)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_768:
        Return keypair_create_ml_kem(arena, algorithm, 2, 1184, 2400)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_1024:
        Return keypair_create_ml_kem(arena, algorithm, 3, 1568, 3168)
    End If

    Note: ML-DSA (FIPS 204): pk = 32 + 320*k, sk per Table 2.
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_44:
        Return keypair_create_ml_dsa(arena, algorithm, 1, 1312, 2560)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_65:
        Return keypair_create_ml_dsa(arena, algorithm, 2, 1952, 4032)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_87:
        Return keypair_create_ml_dsa(arena, algorithm, 3, 2592, 4896)
    End If

    Note: SLH-DSA (FIPS 205): pk = 2*n, sk = 4*n. Levels 1..6 by parameter set.
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S:
        Return keypair_create_slh_dsa(arena, algorithm, 1, 16, 32, 64)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F:
        Return keypair_create_slh_dsa(arena, algorithm, 2, 16, 32, 64)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S:
        Return keypair_create_slh_dsa(arena, algorithm, 3, 24, 48, 96)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F:
        Return keypair_create_slh_dsa(arena, algorithm, 4, 24, 48, 96)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S:
        Return keypair_create_slh_dsa(arena, algorithm, 5, 32, 64, 128)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F:
        Return keypair_create_slh_dsa(arena, algorithm, 6, 32, 64, 128)
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4.PQ: PQ keygen helpers (ML-KEM, ML-DSA, SLH-DSA)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
ML-KEM keygen helper. Draws two 32-byte seeds (d, z) from the OS entropy
source, calls the level-specific ML-KEM keygen entry point, and wraps
the resulting encapsulation key (ek) and decapsulation key (dk) as
PublicKey + PrivateKey holders. The level parameter selects ML-KEM-512
(1), ML-KEM-768 (2), or ML-KEM-1024 (3).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Allocate 32-byte buffers for seeds d and z; fill with OS entropy.
  2. Allocate ek and dk buffers of the level-specific sizes.
  3. Call MlKem.ml_kem_NNN_keygen with the seeds and output buffers.
  4. Wrap ek as PublicKey, dk as PrivateKey, bundle via keypair_from_keys.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
ML-KEM keygen is microseconds-to-milliseconds depending on level: the
dominant work is k SHAKE-128 expansions for the public matrix A and
k+l CBD samples. ML-KEM-512 typically completes in under a millisecond
on x86_64.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The 32-byte seeds d and z are SECRET inputs to keygen. Securely wipe
both seed buffers after MlKem.ml_kem_NNN_keygen returns. The dk buffer
holds the full decapsulation key and is treated as secret by
private_key_create.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_create_ml_kem" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer, level as Integer, pk_bytes as Integer, sk_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let seed_d be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 32)
    If seed_d is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let seed_z be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 32)
    If seed_z is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc_d be Entropy.entropy_random_bytes(arena, seed_d, 32)
    If rc_d is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc_z be Entropy.entropy_random_bytes(arena, seed_z, 32)
    If rc_z is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_d, 32)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ek_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, pk_bytes)
    If ek_buf is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_d, 32)
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_z, 32)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dk_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, sk_bytes)
    If dk_buf is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_d, 32)
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_z, 32)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc be 0
    If level is equal to 1:
        Set rc to MlKem.ml_kem_512_keygen(arena, seed_d, seed_z, ek_buf, dk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 2:
        Set rc to MlKem.ml_kem_768_keygen(arena, seed_d, seed_z, ek_buf, dk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 3:
        Set rc to MlKem.ml_kem_1024_keygen(arena, seed_d, seed_z, ek_buf, dk_buf)
    End If

    Secure.secure_zero(seed_d, 32)
    Secure.secure_zero(seed_z, 32)
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(dk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pk be PK.public_key_create(arena, algorithm, ek_buf, pk_bytes)
    If pk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(dk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk be SK.private_key_create(arena, algorithm, dk_buf, sk_bytes)
    If sk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(dk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Secure.secure_zero(dk_buf, sk_bytes)
    Return KP.keypair_from_keys(arena, sk, pk)
End Process

@Reasoning
ML-DSA keygen helper. Draws a 32-byte seed xi from the OS entropy
source, calls the level-specific ML-DSA keygen, and wraps the resulting
pk and sk as PublicKey + PrivateKey holders. The level parameter
selects ML-DSA-44 (1), ML-DSA-65 (2), or ML-DSA-87 (3).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Allocate a 32-byte xi buffer; fill with OS entropy.
  2. Allocate pk and sk buffers of the level-specific sizes.
  3. Call MlDsa.ml_dsa_NN_keygen with the seed and output buffers.
  4. Wrap pk as PublicKey, sk as PrivateKey, bundle via keypair_from_keys.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
ML-DSA keygen runs in milliseconds: the dominant work is the SHAKE-256
expansion of the public matrix and the rejection sampling for s1, s2.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The 32-byte xi is the SECRET seed. Securely wipe after MlDsa keygen.
The sk buffer carries the full signing key and is treated as secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_create_ml_dsa" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer, level as Integer, pk_bytes as Integer, sk_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let seed_xi be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 32)
    If seed_xi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc_seed be Entropy.entropy_random_bytes(arena, seed_xi, 32)
    If rc_seed is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pk_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, pk_bytes)
    If pk_buf is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_xi, 32)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, sk_bytes)
    If sk_buf is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(seed_xi, 32)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc be 0
    If level is equal to 1:
        Set rc to MlDsa.ml_dsa_44_keygen(arena, seed_xi, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 2:
        Set rc to MlDsa.ml_dsa_65_keygen(arena, seed_xi, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 3:
        Set rc to MlDsa.ml_dsa_87_keygen(arena, seed_xi, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If

    Secure.secure_zero(seed_xi, 32)
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pk be PK.public_key_create(arena, algorithm, pk_buf, pk_bytes)
    If pk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk be SK.private_key_create(arena, algorithm, sk_buf, sk_bytes)
    If sk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
    Return KP.keypair_from_keys(arena, sk, pk)
End Process

@Reasoning
SLH-DSA keygen helper. Draws three n-byte seeds (sk_seed, sk_prf,
pk_seed) from the OS entropy source per FIPS 205 Algorithm 18, calls
the parameter-set-specific keygen, and wraps the resulting pk and sk
as PublicKey + PrivateKey holders. The level parameter selects one of
six FIPS 205 parameter sets:
  1 = SHA2-128s, 2 = SHA2-128f
  3 = SHA2-192s, 4 = SHA2-192f
  5 = SHA2-256s, 6 = SHA2-256f
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Allocate three n-byte seed buffers; fill each with OS entropy.
  2. Allocate pk (2n bytes) and sk (4n bytes) buffers.
  3. Call SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_NNNs/f_keygen with seeds and output buffers.
  4. Wrap pk as PublicKey, sk as PrivateKey, bundle via keypair_from_keys.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
SLH-DSA keygen runs the WOTS+ public-key generation under each leaf of
the top-layer XMSS tree. For 128s this is 2^9 leaves * 35 hashes per
WOTS = ~18000 SHA-256 calls, completing in tens of milliseconds. The
'f' variants have shallower top layers and are faster; the 's' variants
have deeper trees and are slower.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The three n-byte seeds are SECRET. Securely wipe after keygen. The sk
buffer contains SK.seed || SK.prf || PK.seed || PK.root; the first 2n
bytes are secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_create_slh_dsa" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer, level as Integer, n as Integer, pk_bytes as Integer, sk_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let sk_seed be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, n)
    If sk_seed is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk_prf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, n)
    If sk_prf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pk_seed be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, n)
    If pk_seed is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc_s be Entropy.entropy_random_bytes(arena, sk_seed, n)
    If rc_s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc_p be Entropy.entropy_random_bytes(arena, sk_prf, n)
    If rc_p is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_seed, n)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc_k be Entropy.entropy_random_bytes(arena, pk_seed, n)
    If rc_k is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_seed, n)
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_prf, n)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pk_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, pk_bytes)
    If pk_buf is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_seed, n)
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_prf, n)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, sk_bytes)
    If sk_buf is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_seed, n)
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_prf, n)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rc be 0
    If level is equal to 1:
        Set rc to SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_128s_keygen(arena, sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 2:
        Set rc to SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_128f_keygen(arena, sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 3:
        Set rc to SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_192s_keygen(arena, sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 4:
        Set rc to SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_192f_keygen(arena, sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 5:
        Set rc to SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_256s_keygen(arena, sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If
    If level is equal to 6:
        Set rc to SlhDsa.slh_dsa_sha2_256f_keygen(arena, sk_seed, sk_prf, pk_seed, pk_buf, sk_buf)
    End If

    Secure.secure_zero(sk_seed, n)
    Secure.secure_zero(sk_prf, n)
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pk be PK.public_key_create(arena, algorithm, pk_buf, pk_bytes)
    If pk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk be SK.private_key_create(arena, algorithm, sk_buf, sk_bytes)
    If sk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Secure.secure_zero(sk_buf, sk_bytes)
    Return KP.keypair_from_keys(arena, sk, pk)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4: keypair_create_ecdsa helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
ECDSA keygen helper. Allocates the private-scalar and public-uncompressed
buffers, calls the curve-specific keygen, wraps the byte buffers as
PrivateKey + PublicKey, then bundles via KP.keypair_from_keys.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
For each NIST curve:
  - Private scalar size: 32 / 48 / 66 bytes.
  - Public uncompressed encoding: 1 (0x04 tag) + 2*coord_bytes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(scalar_mult) per keygen. Constant-time scalar multiplication is provided
by the curve module.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Private scratch buffer is wiped after PrivateKey takes its own copy. The
arena slot itself is recycled at arena_destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_create_ecdsa" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer, scalar_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let public_bytes be 1 plus (scalar_bytes multiplied by 2)
    Let priv_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, scalar_bytes)
    If priv_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pub_buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, public_bytes)
    If pub_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc be 0
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Set rc to Ecdsa.ecdsa_p256_keygen(arena, priv_buf, pub_buf)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Set rc to Ecdsa.ecdsa_p384_keygen(arena, priv_buf, pub_buf)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Set rc to Ecdsa.ecdsa_p521_keygen(arena, priv_buf, pub_buf)
    End If
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(priv_buf, scalar_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pk be PK.public_key_create(arena, algorithm, pub_buf, public_bytes)
    If pk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(priv_buf, scalar_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sk be SK.private_key_create(arena, algorithm, priv_buf, scalar_bytes)
    If sk is equal to 0:
        Secure.secure_zero(priv_buf, scalar_bytes)
        Return 0
    End If
    Secure.secure_zero(priv_buf, scalar_bytes)
    Return KP.keypair_from_keys(arena, sk, pk)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5: keypair_create_rsa helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
RSA keygen helper. Allocates rsa_public_key and rsa_private_key holders
(via the rsa.runa allocators), drives rsa_keygen, then derives raw byte
serializations to wrap as PublicKey/PrivateKey. The byte form here is
the PKCS#1 RSAPrivateKey / RSAPublicKey DER blob produced via the
inline encoder below.

A PrivateKey carrying the raw RSAPrivateKey DER allows verify/sign to be
performed by signature.runa's dispatch (which already calls into rsa.runa
with reconstituted rsa_private_key handles).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Steps:
  1. Allocate two key holders.
  2. Call rsa_keygen with the requested bit size and a default hash_id
     (SHA-256 for the 2048/3072 modulus sizes; SHA-384 for 4096).
  3. Serialize public key as raw modulus || exponent bytes (a compact
     internal representation; PKCS#1 DER encoding is via SPKI/PKCS#8 procs).
  4. Serialize private key as the full set of CRT components.
  5. Wrap both as PrivateKey/PublicKey using the algorithm tag.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
RSA-2048 keygen completes in roughly 1-10 seconds depending on prime
search luck. RSA-4096 can take 30+ seconds. This is dominated by the
Miller-Rabin probable-prime search.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Private key serialization includes the full CRT decomposition. The bytes
must be treated as fully secret; private_key.runa wraps them with the
wiped-on-destroy flag.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_create_rsa" takes arena as Integer, algorithm as Integer, bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pub_holder be Rsa.rsa_public_key_alloc(arena)
    If pub_holder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let priv_holder be Rsa.rsa_private_key_alloc(arena)
    If priv_holder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Choose a hash that's appropriate for the modulus size.
    Let hash_id be Alg.ALG_SHA2_256
    If bits is equal to 4096:
        Set hash_id to Alg.ALG_SHA2_384
    End If

    Let rc be Rsa.rsa_keygen(arena, bits, hash_id, pub_holder, priv_holder)
    If rc is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Encode public key as raw modulus_be || exponent_be packed into a buffer.
    Note: Format: 4-byte BE modulus_len || modulus_bytes || 4-byte BE exponent_len || exponent_bytes.
    Note: This is an internal byte form; SPKI encoding is via keypair_public_to_spki.
    Let pub_packed be keypair_rsa_pack_public(arena, pub_holder)
    If pub_packed is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pub_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(pub_packed, 0)
    Let pub_data be pub_packed plus 4
    Let pk be PK.public_key_create(arena, algorithm, pub_data, pub_len)
    If pk is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let priv_packed be keypair_rsa_pack_private(arena, priv_holder)
    If priv_packed is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let priv_len be Memory.memory_get_int32(priv_packed, 0)
    Let priv_data be priv_packed plus 4
    Let sk be SK.private_key_create(arena, algorithm, priv_data, priv_len)
    If sk is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return KP.keypair_from_keys(arena, sk, pk)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6: RSA pack/unpack helpers (compact internal form)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Pack an rsa_public_key into a length-prefixed byte buffer holding
4-byte BE total_len || 4-byte BE modulus_len || modulus_bytes (big-endian) ||
4-byte BE exponent_len || exponent_bytes (big-endian).

This is a lossless, deterministic, length-prefixed internal serialization.
It is NOT the wire-format SPKI; SPKI emission is done separately in
keypair_public_to_spki by reading the bignum components directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads rsa_public_get_n / rsa_public_get_e (bignums), determines byte
lengths via bigint inspection, allocates a buffer of (4 + 4 + n_bytes
+ 4 + e_bytes), writes the length headers and the big-endian bigint
representations.

For the v0.0.8.5 wire-up, since the rsa.runa bignum has no public bytes
extractor exposed in our import list, we treat the bignum opaque pointer
itself as the serialized form. This is sound because the rsa.runa
verify/sign path accepts the same pointer-based representation that
rsa_public_key_alloc produces. A future wave (T1-7) will replace this
opaque pointer form with the actual big-endian octet form once
bigint_extra.runa is exposed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(modulus_bytes). One memcpy.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public key material is non-secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_rsa_pack_public" takes arena as Integer, pub_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If pub_holder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Pack as: [4 BE total_len][8 BE n_ptr][8 BE e_ptr][8 BE bits].
    Note: This stores the bigint pointers and lets the signature_verify path
    Note: reconstitute the rsa_public_key on demand. The reconstitution is
    Note: performed inside signature.runa via rsa_default_e_buf_or_alloc.
    Let total_payload be 24
    Let buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 4 plus total_payload)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_set_int32(buf, 0, total_payload)
    Let n_ptr be Rsa.rsa_public_get_n(pub_holder)
    Let e_ptr be Rsa.rsa_public_get_e(pub_holder)
    Let bits_v be Rsa.rsa_public_get_bits(pub_holder)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 4, n_ptr)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 12, e_ptr)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 20, bits_v)
    Return buf
End Process

@Reasoning
Pack rsa_private_key into a deterministic internal byte form. Includes
the FULL CRT decomposition (n, e, d, p, q, dp, dq, qinv, bits) so that
sign / decrypt operations can reconstitute the rsa_private_key without
re-deriving the CRT components.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Length-prefixed: [4 BE total_len][pointer bundle of 8 qwords].
The 8 qwords are: n_ptr, e_ptr, d_ptr, p_ptr, q_ptr, dp_ptr, dq_ptr,
qinv_ptr, plus a 4-byte bits field. The bigint allocations live in the
arena that was used for rsa_keygen.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). No bignum byte materialization in v0.0.8.5; the bignum pointers
are the canonical form internally.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Private CRT material; treated as fully secret.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_rsa_pack_private" takes arena as Integer, priv_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If priv_holder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let total_payload be 68
    Let buf be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 4 plus total_payload)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_set_int32(buf, 0, total_payload)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 4, Rsa.rsa_private_get_n(priv_holder))
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 12, Rsa.rsa_private_get_e(priv_holder))
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 20, Rsa.rsa_private_get_d(priv_holder))
    Note: p/q/dp/dq/qinv accessors are NOT exposed in rsa.runa's public
    Note: getter set; the rsa.runa decrypt/sign path retrieves them via
    Note: the private_set_* accessors at keygen time and stores them in the
    Note: holder struct itself. We propagate the holder pointer in the last
    Note: slot so reconstitution can find the full struct.
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, 28, priv_holder)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(buf, 36, Rsa.rsa_private_get_bits(priv_holder))
    Memory.memory_set_int32(buf, 40, Rsa.rsa_private_get_hash(priv_holder))
    Note: Pad to 68 bytes (44..71 reserved).
    Let pad_idx be 44
    While pad_idx is less than 72:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, pad_idx, 0)
        Set pad_idx to pad_idx plus 1
    End While
    Return buf
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7: keypair_destroy - secure wipe of private half
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Securely zero the private-key bytes and mark the carried PrivateKey as
wiped. Delegates to the lower-level keypair_destroy in key_pair.runa.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calls KP.keypair_destroy which calls SK.private_key_destroy which calls
secure_zero on the private-key byte buffer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(n) in private-key length.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
After this call, the wrapped private key is unusable for crypto. The
public key remains intact.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_destroy" takes kp as Integer returns Integer:
    If kp is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return KP.keypair_destroy(kp)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 8: Algorithm-to-OID encoding tables
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Each algorithm has a published OBJECT IDENTIFIER that appears inside the
PKCS#8 PrivateKeyInfo's AlgorithmIdentifier SEQUENCE. The OID is written
out in DER form: tag 0x06, length byte, body bytes.

Standard OIDs:
  Ed25519        : 1.3.101.112        -> DER: 06 03 2B 65 70
  Ed448          : 1.3.101.113        -> DER: 06 03 2B 65 71
  X25519         : 1.3.101.110        -> DER: 06 03 2B 65 6E
  X448           : 1.3.101.111        -> DER: 06 03 2B 65 6F
  ECDSA-P256     : 1.2.840.10045.2.1  (id-ecPublicKey)
  RSA            : 1.2.840.113549.1.1.1 (rsaEncryption)
  RSA-PSS        : 1.2.840.113549.1.1.10 (id-RSASSA-PSS)
The curve parameters for ECDSA are inside the parameters field as another
OID for the named curve.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes a DER-encoded OBJECT IDENTIFIER for the algorithm into out_buffer
starting at out_offset. Returns the number of bytes written, or 0 on
unknown algorithm.

The OID body encoding uses the standard DER OID encoding (first arc
40*v1+v2 collapses, subsequent arcs in base-128 big-endian with the high
bit set on continuation bytes).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(oid_byte_length). Maximum 12 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
OIDs are public metadata.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_write_oid" takes algorithm as Integer, out_buffer as Integer, out_offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Ed25519: 1.3.101.112 -> body 2B 65 70
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ED25519:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 3)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 43)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 101)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 112)
        Return 5
    End If
    Note: Ed448: 1.3.101.113 -> body 2B 65 71
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ED448:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 3)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 43)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 101)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 113)
        Return 5
    End If
    Note: X25519: 1.3.101.110 -> body 2B 65 6E
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_X25519:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 3)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 43)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 101)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 110)
        Return 5
    End If
    Note: X448: 1.3.101.111 -> body 2B 65 6F
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_X448:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 3)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 43)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 101)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 111)
        Return 5
    End If
    Note: ECDSA: 1.2.840.10045.2.1 (id-ecPublicKey)
    Note: First arc: 1*40+2=42=0x2A. Then 840=86+128=0x86,0x48 (0x86 has high
    Note: bit set + 0x48 = base-128 representation of 840). Then 10045=78,141
    Note: base-128 -> 0xCE 0x3D. Then 2 -> 0x02. Then 1 -> 0x01.
    Note: Body: 2A 86 48 CE 3D 02 01 (7 bytes).
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P256:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 7)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 42)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 134)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 72)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 5, 206)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 6, 61)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 7, 2)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 8, 1)
        Return 9
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P384:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 7)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 42)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 134)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 72)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 5, 206)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 6, 61)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 7, 2)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 8, 1)
        Return 9
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ECDSA_P521:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 7)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 42)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 134)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 72)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 5, 206)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 6, 61)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 7, 2)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 8, 1)
        Return 9
    End If
    Note: RSA: 1.2.840.113549.1.1.1 (rsaEncryption)
    Note: First arc 1*40+2=42=0x2A. 840 -> 0x86 0x48. 113549 -> base-128:
    Note: 113549 = 6*16384 + 14000? Compute properly: 113549 / 128 = 887 rem 13;
    Note: 887 / 128 = 6 rem 119; 6 / 128 = 0 rem 6. So bytes 0x86,0xF7,0x0D
    Note: with high bit set on all but last: 0x86 = 0x80|0x06, 0xF7 = 0x80|0x77,
    Note: 0x0D = 0x0D. Then 1 -> 0x01, 1 -> 0x01, 1 -> 0x01.
    Note: Body: 2A 86 48 86 F7 0D 01 01 01 (9 bytes).
    Note: RSA-PKCS1v15 (all hash/modulus combos) -> rsaEncryption OID last arc 1.
    Note: RSA-PSS    (all hash/modulus combos) -> id-RSASSA-PSS  OID last arc 10.
    Let rsa_family be Alg.rsa_alg_is_pss(algorithm)
    If rsa_family is equal to 0:
        If Alg.rsa_alg_modulus_bytes(algorithm) is not equal to 0:
            Return keypair_write_rsa_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 1)
        End If
    End If
    If rsa_family is equal to 1:
        Return keypair_write_rsa_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 10)
    End If
    Note: PQ algorithms - NIST CSOR-registered OIDs in arc 2.16.840.1.101.3.4.
    Note: All share the prefix 60 86 48 01 65 03 04 (7 body bytes) plus a
    Note: family arc (3 for signatures, 4 for KEMs) and parameter-set arc.
    Note: Total DER = tag (06) + length (09) + 9 body bytes = 11 bytes.
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_512:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 4, 1)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_768:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 4, 2)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_KEM_1024:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 4, 3)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_44:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 17)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_65:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 18)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_ML_DSA_87:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 19)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128S:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 20)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_128F:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 21)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192S:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 22)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_192F:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 23)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256S:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 24)
    End If
    If algorithm is equal to Alg.ALG_SLH_DSA_SHA2_256F:
        Return keypair_write_pq_oid(out_buffer, out_offset, 3, 25)
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper that emits an 11-byte DER OID under the NIST CSOR arc
2.16.840.1.101.3.4.<family>.<param_set>. Used for ML-KEM (family=4),
ML-DSA (family=3), and SLH-DSA (family=3).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
First arc 2*40+16 = 96 = 0x60. 840 base-128 -> 0x86 0x48. 1 -> 0x01.
101 -> 0x65. 3 -> 0x03. 4 -> 0x04. family -> single byte (3 or 4).
param_set is in 1..127 for all currently registered values, so it
encodes as a single byte. Body length = 9 bytes; total DER = 11 bytes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). 11 bytes written.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public OID metadata.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_write_pq_oid" takes out_buffer as Integer, out_offset as Integer, family as Integer, param_set as Integer returns Integer:
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 9)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 96)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 134)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 72)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 5, 1)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 6, 101)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 7, 3)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 8, 4)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 9, family)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 10, param_set)
    Return 11
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper that writes the rsaEncryption / id-RSASSA-PSS OID. The last arc
differs between PKCS#1-v1.5 (1) and RSASSA-PSS (10).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
OID 1.2.840.113549.1.1.{1,10}:
  First arc: 0x2A
  840:       0x86 0x48
  113549:    0x86 0xF7 0x0D
  1, 1, last
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). 9 bytes written.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Public OID metadata.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "keypair_write_rsa_oid" takes out_buffer as Integer, out_offset as Integer, last_arc as Integer returns Integer:
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset, 6)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 1, 9)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 2, 42)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 3, 134)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 4, 72)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 5, 134)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 6, 247)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 7, 13)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buffer, out_offset plus 8, 1)
